[[File:Ojiharinamawakahime-jinja torii.JPG|thumb|200px|right|Torii]]
'''Ojiharinamawakahime Shrine''' (おじはりなまわかひめじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Kita-ku (Okayama)|Q855478|WD=Q855478|lt=Kita-ku|1=Kita-ku, Okayama}}, {{ill|lt=Okayama|Q200078|WD=Q200078|1=Okayama}}, {{ill|lt=Okayama Prefecture|Q132936|WD=Q132936|1=Okayama Prefecture}}. It is a successor shrine of a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}, and its former rank was {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* Ojiharinamawakahime-no-Mikoto

=== History ===
In the mid-{{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|WD=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}' lists "Ojiharinamawakahime Shrine" in {{ill|lt=Mino District (Bizen)|Q11071226|WD=Q11071226|1=Mino district}} of {{ill|lt=Bizen Province|Q1053688|WD=Q1053688|1=Bizen Province}}, ranking it as {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}. In the '{{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Bizen no Kuni Jinmyōchō|1=UNKNOWN}},' the Sōja manuscript records "Owari Harita Mawakahime Shrine," and the Yamamoto manuscript records "Junior Fourth Rank Lower Owari Harita Myōjin"<ref name="神社庁">[http://www.okayama-jinjacho.or.jp/cgi-bin/jsearch.cgi?mode=detail&jcode=01046 Ojiharinamawakahime Shrine] (Okayama Prefectural Shrine Association).</ref>.

Near this shrine is a mountain called "Handa-yama," said to be a mistaken form of "Harita-yama," and the name "Harita" is said to derive from this shrine<ref name="神社庁"/>. The shrine name suggests relation to the {{ill|lt=Owari clan|Q11465311|WD=Q11465311|1=Owari clan}}, also supported by nearby {{ill|lt=Obari Shrine|Q17226111|WD=Q17226111|1=Ohari Shrine}}, another Shikinaisha associated with the Owari clan. Related theories include westward migration of the Owari clan from Owari<ref>Recorded in the Meiji-period 'Engishiki Inner Shrines and Kokushi Existing Shrines' (Obari Shrine section in 'Gods of Japan - Shrines and Sacred Places - 2 Sanyō and Shikoku' ({{ill|lt=Hakusuisha|Q4346470|WD=Q4346470|1=Hakusuisha Publishing}})).</ref>, and conversely eastward migration from Kibi to Owari<ref>Hiroaki Shimoyama, "Were the ancient Owari clan migrants eastward from Kibi?" ('Okayama Prefecture Mystery Walks,' Shinjinbutsu Bunko).</ref>.

However, Ojiharinamawakahime Shrine was formerly worshiped at the present Misaki-gū site (Kitagata, Kita-ku, Okayama; {{ウィキ座標|34|41|05.76|N|133|56|04.24|E|region:JP-33_type:landmark|位置|name=Misaki-gū (former site)}}), where Amatsu Shrine had been worshiped<ref name="玄松子">[http://www.genbu.net/data/bizen/ojiharina_title.htm Ojiharinamawakahime Shrine] (Genmatsuko personal site).</ref>. After entering Meiji, Ojiharinamawakahime Shrine was moved here and Amatsu Shrine became a precinct end shrine<ref name="玄松子"/>.

Under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, it was ranked {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}.

